spanGrp.span: Yís antepasado-wa je beteũ-te rö Talamanka
Two of them escaped… to Ujarraz.
b-ol wa ña eskapa-wa-ũte Jie-wa të Ujarras (_) Ujarras
They brought their kids and lived;
jie-wa wã yabla beté í wa Í se-nã'
they hunt pacas, peccaries and so on, and panted bananas, mandioc.
(_) jie-wa të rö eree kasri bi kono bi jirö bi te-gẽ jemẽ chomõ í rö shkö bi rö je bötö-gẽ je ke-gẽ-ite
They cooked all that and raised their children that way;
Je wa í ũlĩwã-gẽ yabla kebiwẽ-gẽ-ite
they would smash the bananas so the kids could eat or drink them.
yabla ĩa chomõ wötue-gẽ-ite mẽ-gẽ-ite guya-lë o ya-lë
There they lived and worked only.
Jeska jie-wa ser-gẽ rö (hm) shkablö wa jebö
They would plant or else sometimes they went hunting and thus fed themselves.
Jie-wa mi-gẽu-lo jirö kö jirö kö o si no mĩgalela í she-gẽ-ite-nã í mĩ-gẽu-lo rö jirö ktö Je je wa í ña chewa-gẽ jela
We grew up like that long ago.
Jie-wa jebi jiska ñã jiñãra sa kebi-lë rö ta (_) miga beteũ-te taranã ka pe sẽr kũnã ĩã jebi
For quite sometime until now some still live like that;
Maleska maleska-wa bö nẽ ser-gẽ jebi rö
they say that when they grew up they would invite the others, and sometimes they would take us… they just lived in the bush;
Pa-gẽ-ite jela-nã ji ñãla nã (_) jie-wa kebir-gẽ-ra í mĩ-gẽ siga-wa kiö je invitarwe-gẽ-ite migalera je sa tse-gẽ-ite ĩã jemẽ ere ere migale jie-wa jie-wa rö se-nã' kã'jãrga wa jebö
they did not live in houses;
jie-wa ka rö sẽr jũ nã
they would purify themselves and took care of things like pigs, dogs and cats, of which they had lots.
jie-wa rö jirö betsö (_) jirö könãnã (_) kuchi bi chichi bi michi bi tsõ tã'ĩ
They fed the cows; they always had things to do, not like other people.
Jie-wa wã baga chẽwã jirö wã jirö wã wãjebö jie-wa ka ka ka kunã maleska-wa bi bi ser-gẽ
In some cases they would take their children along to work and would teach them how to work.
Jie-wa rö shkablö wajebö jemẽ ere maleska-wa ra nã yabla mi-gẽ mi-gẽ í wa shkablö jiebi Yabla yue-gẽ-ite shkablö jirö kkö
When they grew up, they would be able to harvest even if they are still little.
Jebi ra yabla degau-lo-ka keyëge-ra jirö jirö tse-gẽ-ka Jie-wa rö yuliski-gla-wa-ra jie-wa të jirö jirö í wakwa të í tke-gẽ-ka í wakwa të jirö wẽ-gẽ-ka
They could plant and do things by themselves, like dry-banana drink, ripe banana drink; they would make lots of chicha out of corn on the cob.
Jie-wa të tú jie-wa të chomõli jie-wa të ere kwö' dulunã wẽ-gẽ tã'ĩ di ye jirö ye
